These have to be the best cookies in the history of the cookie-making world. I found this recipe when I was looking for something I could pass off as a relatively healthy snack for a girls basketball team. The coaches had been adamant that pre-game bus-ride snacks had to be healthy, so I was a little apprehensive after sending this (along with apple slices) when it was our turn for snacks. Not to worry, the players and the coaches loved them and politely asked for more. I have since made them countless times, with many variations, and they are always wonderful. I had a few disasters trying to grate chocolate (there is some static electricity thing that goes on and makes the chocolate fly around uncontrollably), so instead of adding grated chocolate, I have used a little melted chocolate, grated chocolate (the kind for making hot chocolate) and even Nutella. But generally, I leave the grated chocolate and substitutes out. I usually add lots of coarsely chopped walnuts or pecans. And I often add more oats than called for. Alway, always, they are wonderful. Sometimes I bake half the batch, then form the rest into slightly flattened disks, freeze them, then keep them in a zipper bag in the freezer for use whenever they're needed. (And I discovered in this way that the frozen dough is a pretty good treat, too!)

