Rating: 3
For those of you who mentioned not liking the "taste" of the baking soda or baking powder (how you can taste these is beyond me), you can easily remedy this. First, baking soda is of course the leavening (in addition to the powder), but being an alkaline, it's used to neutralize the acidity from the brown sugar (molasses is acidic) and chocolate (also acidic). Just replace the soda with all powder. Just know that you're not mellowing out the aciditiy that is provided by the br. sugar and chocolate - not that it's bad! Use about 2 tsp. more baking powder. First smell your baking soda and make sure it's fresh. Those who don't like the taste of baking powder (which is even more odd to be able to taste this with all of the other strong flavors - esp. only 1/2 tsp in the entire recipe), omit the baking powder and add about 1/4 to 1/2 tsp. more baking soda. But I have a feeling it's not the baking powder itself you're tasting but spoilage. A lot of people keep this in their cupboards or refrigerators WAY past their expiration date. Or maybe you do have an aversion to aluminum-based ingredients! If that's the case, do try the other types of baking powders. Until then, try to just substitute baking soda (but be aware of the differing proportions used and the fact that the powder has a neutralizing agent that the alkaline soda doesn't have). I'm sure I'll see a lot of posts saying "you can't just substitute one for the other!" No, often you can't. But sometimes, with some ingredients, in some recipes, you can. Especially with baking, you have to know when you can and can't change or substitute something. I'm a baker. Baking is what I do. Through a lot of trial an error, I've learned what can and can't be changed. This is a time when you can. As most of you have noticed, these cookies are like muffins... they can withstand about 30 - 40% variation in several of the ingredients before you actually screw 'em up.

