Rating: 3
I'm not a big fan of chocolate chip cookies, but these are probably The Ultimate Cookie. My coworkers loved them. The oats and peanut butter add flavor and texture. The flattened-ball method gives a nice, tidy appearance. These are a LOT more work than your average cookie. The grated chocolate was a major pain. I tried two methods: a) grating into a container with a special grater lid, which made an ungodly mess of chocolate bits flying everywhere and led the chocolate to melt all over my fingers even after I chilled it first; and b) chopping the chocolate in the mini-food processor, which was easier but left the chocolate looking sort of chewed-up and crumbly rather than flaked and also made a huge din. Betweeen the two methods, I'd say only seven of the original eight ounces made it into the dough. In the future I'll probably stick with method b, or else skip the chocolate entirely. I used natural PB because I didn't want to buy a whole jar of the nasty hydrogenated stuff just for one recipe, and it worked fine. Chilling the dough makes it much easier to shape and prevents the cookies from overbaking. Hint: the bottom of a glass dipped in water is a handy tool for flattening the dough balls. The bottom line: I recommend this recipe highly, if you have a little time on your hands and are really striving for the ultimate cookie.

